  <h>toponymic proper nouns</h>
  <p>Toponymic proper nouns are <a href="?xx=nouns/proper_nouns">proper nouns</a> which are also <a
      href="?xx=nouns/toponyms">toponyms</a>, i.e. they name places (geographical entities).</p>

  <section id="deps">
    <h>dependents</h>
    <p>Like other proper nouns, toponymic proper nouns can be modified by an attributive
        <emph>adjective</emph> eg. <m>Alba Nuadh</m>
      <en>Nova Scotia</en>, <m>Sasainn Nuadh</m>
      <en>New England</en>, <m>Lannraig Ùr</m>
      <en>New Lanark</en>, <m>Beàrnaraigh Mòr</m>
      <en>Great Bernera</en>, <m>Lodainn Meadhanach</m>
      <en>Midlothian</en> (but <g>Meadhan-Aimearaga</g>
      <en>Central America</en>).</p>
    <p>Toponymic proper nouns can be modified by one of the following four directional prepositional
      phrases – <ul>
        <li><g>a Tuath</g>
          <en>North(ern)</en> eg. <m>Uibhist a Tuath</m>
          <en>North Uist</en>, <m>Aimearaga a Tuath</m>
          <en>North America</en></li>
        <li><g>a Deas</g>
          <en>South(ern)</en> eg. <m>Uibhist a Deas</m>
          <en>South Uist</en>, <m>Afraga a Deas</m>
          <en>South(ern) Africa</en></li>
        <li><g>an Ear</g>
          <en>East(ern)</en> eg. <m>Ros an Ear</m>
          <en>Easter Ross</en>, <m>Lodainn an Ear</m>
          <en>East Lothian</en></li>
        <li><g>an Iar</g>
          <en>West(ern)</en> eg. <m>Ros an Iar</m>
          <en>Wester Ross</en>, <m>Lodainn an Iar</m>
          <en>West Lothian</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>Toponymic proper nouns can be modified by one of the following two directional adjectives – <ul>
        <li><g>Uachdarach</g>
          <en>Upper</en> eg. <m>Pabail Uarach</m>
          <en>Upper Bayble</en>, <m>Canada Uachdarach</m>
          <en>Upper Canada</en></li>
        <li><g>Ìochdarach</g>
          <en>Lower</en> eg. <m>Pabail Iarach</m>
          <en>Lower Bayble</en>, <m>Canada Ìochdarach</m>
          <en>Lower Canada</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>
  <section id="uses">
    <h>uses</h>
    <p>Like other toponyms, toponymic proper nouns can be classified <emph>semantically</emph>
      according to the kind of geographical entity they refer to – <ul>
        <li>islands and districts eg. <m>Cataibh</m>
          <en>Sutherland</en>, <m>Barraigh</m>
          <en>Barra</en>
          <!-- <boxlink ref="#districts"/> --></li>
        <li>towns and settlements eg. <m>Glaschu</m>
          <en>Glasgow</en>, <m>Siabost</m>
          <en>Shawbost</en>
          <!-- <boxlink ref="#settlements"/> --></li>
        <li>countries and continents eg. <a href="?gd=Alba"><g>Alba</g></a>
          <en>Scotland</en>, <m>Afraga</m>
          <en>Africa</en>
          <!-- <boxlink ref="#countries"/> --></li>
        <li>mountains and uplands eg. <m>Sùilebheinn</m>
          <en>Suilven</en>, <m>Dris</m>
          <en>Driesh</en></li>
        <li>rivers, lakes and seas eg. <m>Cluaidh</m>
          <en>The Clyde</en>, <m>Tatha</m>
          <en>The Tay</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>Toponymic proper nouns are used as roots for <a href="?xx=nouns/demonyms">demonyms</a> –
      adjectives and common nouns describing or referring to a person (or other entity) originating
      from, or otherwise associated with the place identified by the proper noun eg.
        <m>Leòdhasach</m>
      <en>(person) from Lewis</en>, <m>Albannach</m>
      <en>(person) from Scotland</en>.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="lenition">
    <h>lenition</h>
    <p>A toponymic proper noun which is the (genitive) (post-)specifier of another noun is usually
      lenited – <ul>
        <li><g>muinntir Ghlaschu</g>
          <en>the people of Glasgow</en>, cf. <bad>muinntir Glaschu</bad></li>
        <li><g>Banca Shasainn</g> – <en>The Bank of England</en>, cf. <bad>Banca Sasainn</bad></li>
        <li><g>siorrachd Pheairt</g> – <en>the county of Perth</en>, cf. <bad>siorrachd
          Peairt</bad></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>However, this lenition can be ‘blocked’ in certain contexts – <ul>
        <li><g>drochaid T[h]atha</g> – <en>The Tay Bridge</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>



